To produce a SPARQL query for KG2 (OpenAlex) given the instruction and examples, we need to follow these steps:

1. Identify the corresponding entity and relation mapping (ER2) for the given DBLP query.
2. Map the DBLP query to the corresponding OpenAlex query based on the ER2.

The given DBLP query is:
```sql
SELECT (AVG(?count) AS ?answer) { 
  SELECT (COUNT(?y) AS ?count) 
  WHERE { 
    ?x <https://dblp.org/rdf/schema#authoredBy> <https://dblp.org/pid/09/9051> . 
    ?x <https://dblp.org/rdf/schema#yearOfPublication> ?y 
  } 
  GROUP BY ?y 
}
```
The ER2 for KG1 (DBLP) and KG2 (OpenAlex) is:
```json
[
  {
    "DBLP": "https://dblp.org/pid/09/9051",
    "OpenAlex": [
      "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7580-7058"
    ]
  },
  {
    "DBLP": "<https://dblp.org/rdf/schema#authoredBy>",
    "OpenAlex": [
      "https://semopenalex.org/ontology/hasAuthorship",
      "https://semopenalex.org/ontology/hasAuthor"
    ]
  },
  {
    "DBLP": "<https://dblp.org/rdf/schema#yearOfPublication>",
    "OpenAlex": [
      "http://purl.org/spar/fabio/hasPublicationYear"
    ]
  }
]
```
Based on the ER2, we can identify the corresponding mapping for the given DBLP query:

* `?x <https://dblp.org/rdf/schema#authoredBy> <https://dblp.org/pid/09/9051>` maps to `?work oa:hasAuthorship ?authorship . ?authorship oa:hasAuthor ?author . ?author <https://dbpedia.org/ontology/orcidId> "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7580-7058" .`
* `?x <https://dblp.org/rdf/schema#yearOfPublication> ?y` maps to `?work fabio:hasPublicationYear ?year .`

Now, we can construct the OpenAlex query:
```sparql
PREFIX oa: <https://semopenalex.org/ontology/>
PREFIX fabio: <http://purl.org/spar/fabio/>

SELECT (AVG(?count) AS ?answer) {
  SELECT (COUNT(?year) AS ?count)
  WHERE {
    ?work oa:hasAuthorship ?authorship .
    ?authorship oa:hasAuthor ?author .
    ?author <https://dbpedia.org/ontology/orcidId> "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7580-7058" .
    ?work fabio:hasPublicationYear ?year .
  }
  GROUP BY ?year
}
```
However, this query will not return the average number of research papers published per year. To fix this, we need to group the results by year and count the number of papers published in each year, then calculate the average.

Here's the corrected query:
```sparql
PREFIX oa: <https://semopenalex.org/ontology/>
PREFIX fabio: <http://purl.org/spar/fabio/>

SELECT (AVG(?count) AS ?answer) {
  SELECT (COUNT(?work) AS ?count)
  WHERE {
    ?work oa:hasAuthorship ?authorship .
    ?authorship oa:hasAuthor ?author .
    ?author <https://dbpedia.org/ontology/orcidId> "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7580-7058" .
    ?work fabio:hasPublicationYear ?year .
    FILTER (?year >= 2000 && ?year <= 2022)  # assuming the author has published papers in this range
  }
  GROUP BY ?year
}
```
This query will return the average number of research papers published by the author per year.

